\begin_layout Standard
We are pleased to submit our paper 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Structure and function of cells in a neural integrator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for publication as a Report.
 Our submission has four figures.
 It is somewhat over the normal word count.
 We believe this will facilitate evaluation by reviewers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We think our work is appropriate for 
\emph on
Current Biology
\emph default
, because of general interest in two-photon calcium imaging combined with
 serial electron microscopy (EM) as a powerful method for investigating
 the structure and function of neural circuits.
 As you know, this method is still in its infancy, and has previously only
 been applied to study neurons that encode stimulus variables (in mouse
 retina and primary visual cortex).
 Here we apply this method to a population of neurons defined by their encoding
 of 
\emph on
behavioral
\emph default
 variables.
 We focus on neurons carrying eye position signals, which are located in
 a hindbrain neural circuit known as the "velocity-to-position neural integrator
," or "neural integrator" for short.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our study is in the larval zebrafish, and so fits in well with a number
 of other papers published by your journal on circuit neuroscience in this
 model organism, as well as with papers on mouse retinal circuitry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As possible referees, we suggest those who have worked on calcium imaging
 in larval zebrafish, such as Joe Fetcho, Florian Engert, Herwig Baier,
 Kevin Briggman, Misha Ahrens, and Johann Bollmann.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Closing
Sincerely,
\end_layout

